@Ken00001010 you've totally missed the point I was making. I'm talking about the momentum of the water as it descends. My mention of noise and heat was for the pedantic who might say no not all of the speed the water loses goes to the fan, there's energy bled off in other minor ways.
Momentum is always conserved. 
 If it's lost from one place it's gained by, or rather transferred to, another.

@Ken Clements  my understanding of momentum is mass times velocity, and velocity isn't just speed, it's speed in a direction. when the water hits the fan its mass stays the same but velocity (speed in a given direction) has changed. Its momentum is therefore changed, any loss in momentum must be accounted for, it reappears as rotation of the fan. The question I was addressing was about mass/momentum not energy. My addendum was because I assumed that The fan rocking and bouncing under the force of water also robs some of the momentum as it forced in a different direction entirely to the water going sideways. 
Having looked again it's more complicated because the velocity is increasing under gravitational acceleration but that's by the by. 
Sorry if I've annoyed you unknowingly by misunderstanding something.
